nt if installed. Check:\n\n```\nwhich xmllint\n```\n\nBut I'm not sure if it's there. Let's just do a quick-and-dirty grep and cut extraction.\n\nThe structure:\n\n<item>\n<title>...</title>\n<link>...</link>\n<pubDate>...</pubDate>\n...\n</item>\n\nI can do:\n\n```\ncurl -s \"https://www.bing.com/news/search?q=刘亦菲&format=rss\" | awk '/<item>/,/<\\/item>/' | grep -E '<title>|<link>|<pubDate>' | sed -e 's/<[^>]*>//g' -e 's/^[ \\t]*//'\n```\n\nBut that may also include channel title? Actually, the first title appears for the channel? The RSS feed typically starts with channel title and description, but the pattern `<item>`, `</item>` isolates items. So that should work.\n\nBut note: Bing might block curl? Usually it's okay.\n\nLet's try it! It's a quick and simple solution that will yield actual news results. I can then format and present them to the user.\n\nThus, I'll execute a command to fetch and parse. I'll do it in one exec, with pty not needed. I'll capture output and return to user.\n\nI'll run:\n\n```bash\ncurl -s \"https://www.bing.com/news/search?q=刘亦菲&format=rss\" | awk '/<item>/,/<\\/item>/' | while IFS= read -r line; do\n  if [[ $line =~ <title> ]]; then\n    title=$(echo \"$line\" | sed -e 's/<[^>]*>//g')\n    echo \"标题: $title\"\n  elif [[ $line =~ <link> ]]; then\n    link=$(echo \"$line\" | sed -e 's/<[^>]*>//g')\n    echo \"链接: $link\"\n  elif [[ $line =~ <pubDate> ]]; then\n    date=$(echo \"$line\" | sed -e 's/<[^>]*>//g')\n    echo \"日期: $date\"\n    echo \"---\"\n  fi\ndone | head -n 60\n```\n\nBut bash arrays and regex may not be portable. Alternatively, use awk to parse. Simpler: Use xmlstarlet if installed, but likely not.\n\nI can do a simple approach: use `grep -oP` with PCRE to extract content inside tags, but -P may not be available.\n\nGiven constraints, I'll do a pragmatic extraction with sed and grep, and hope the RSS format is consistent.\n\nLet's do:\n\n```bash\ncurl -s \"https://www.bing.com/news/search?q=刘亦菲&format=rss\" |\nawk '\n  /<item>/,/<\\/item>/ {\n    if (/<title>/ && !/channel/) {\n      gsub(/.*<title>|<\\/title>.*/, \"\")\n      print \"标题: \" $0\n    }\n    if (/<link>/) {\n      gsub(/.*<link>|<\\/link>.*/, \"\")\n      print \"链接: \" $0\n    }\n    if (/<pubDate>/) {\n      gsub(/.*<pubDate>|<\\/pubDate>.*/, \"\")\n      print \"日期: \" $0\n      print \"---\"\n    }\n  }\n' | head -n 60\n```\n\nBut the awk might not be precise. Let's test conceptually.\n\nBetter: just extract all titles, links, pubDates within items using a loop. I can do:\n\n```bash\ncurl -s \"https://www.bing.com/news/search?q=刘亦菲&format=rss\" > /tmp/feed.xml\ngrep -A 10 '<item>' /tmp/feed.xml | while IFS= read -r line; do ... done\n```\n\nBut that's messy.\n\nMaybe I can use a tool like `xsltproc`? Unlikely.\n\nGiven this is a quick request, I can just output the raw RSS and let the user read? But the user wants collected news; they probably expect a summary list.\n\nAlternatively, I can use a news API that returns JSON, like GNews, but that requires key. Not.\n\nAnother idea: Use Baidu? But Chinese news? Bing news includes Chinese sources? Possibly. The query \"刘亦菲\" in Bing News will return Chinese results if the system language is Chinese? Not sure. But at least some Chinese sources may appear.\n\nI'll just do the fetch and try to format with simple sed.\n\nLet's write a one-liner:\n\n```bash\ncurl -s \"https://www.bing.com/news/search?q=刘亦菲&format=rss\" |\nsed -n '/<item>/,/<\\/item>/p' |\nsed -e 's/^[ \\t]*//' |\nawk '\n  /<title>/ { gsub(/.*<title>|<\\/title>.*/, \"\"); print \"标题: \" $0 }\n  /<link>/ { gsub(/.*<link>|<\\/link>.*/, \"\"); print \"链接: \" $0 }\n  /<pubDate>/ { gsub(/.*<pubDate>|<\\/pubDate>.*/, \"\"); print \"日期: \" $0; print \"---\" }\n' |\nhead -n 100\n```\n\nThat should work.\n\nBut I'm concerned about the time: I'm in a chat with a user; I should respond quickly. This curl fetch and parse should be fast (<5 sec). So I'll just execute it and present results.\n\nBut note: The user may 