{"type":"message","id":"29f06de7","parentId":"0fc3f229","timestamp":"2026-03-11T13:19:25.912Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Google returns 400. The RSS feed might need a specific parameter? Actually Google News RSS endpoint is often like: https://news.google.com/rss/search?q=... but it may block automated requests.\n\nMaybe we can use a simpler approach: use the \"news\" command from a tool like `newsboat`? Not installed.\n\nGiven the difficulty, perhaps the intended solution is to use the oracle skill in API mode with a model that can access the web (some models have web search capability). But the model would need to be able to browse. However, oracle's API mode doesn't do browsing; it's just a static prompt. The browser mode does the actual browsing.\n\nGiven the time, maybe I should use oracle. But I'm not confident it will work easily in this environment.\n\nLet's think differently: Could I use the `webhooks` command to send a request to a news API? Not.\n\nMaybe the user expects me to just do a quick summary from memory? I could provide known recent news about Liu Yifei from my training data, which goes up to 2024, but not necessarily current 2026. But the user asked for \"网上关于刘亦菲的新闻\" which implies current news from the internet. So I need up-to-date info.\n\nGiven that I'm a language model with a knowledge cutoff (probably 2024), I don't have real-time access. So I must rely on tools that fetch current data. The oracle browser mode would indeed fetch current web pages.\n\nThus, I should use the oracle skill. Even if it's slow, it's the right tool. I'll run it in the background with a long timeout and let the user know it's started. Then they can check the session or I can later poll and present results. However, as the assistant, I may not be able to maintain state across multiple turns in the same session? Actually, I can spawn a process and later check its output. In the same session, I could poll while waiting? But the user will see my messages as I send them. If I start a background process, I could then check its status periodically in the same session? But the session might not stay active that long; but I can send a message that I'm starting and later maybe use a cron job or something.\n\nGiven the complexity and the fact that the user just asked and then we are in a single turn, perhaps I should start the oracle process and then use `process poll` to wait for it? But that would block my response for potentially an hour, which is not acceptable.\n\nInstead, I can start it as a background process and then inform the user that the search is running and will take some time, and that they'll be notified when done or they can check back. I could also note that they can use `oracle status` to monitor.\n\nBut can I start a process and then detach? The `exec` tool with `background: true` will run in the background; I can provide a session ID and they can later use `process` to check logs. But the user may not know how to use that. Better, I could spawn an agent that runs the search and then sends the result to the user via a message? But that would require the agent to have messaging capability, and I'd need to know target. We could use `cron` or `sessions_spawn`. However, it's not necessary; I could just run oracle and then later when it's done, I could read the output and send it as a reply. But that would require me to stay alive or have a way to know when it finishes. In this architecture, the assistant session is temporary; if I start a background process and then the session ends, I may not be able to reattach to that process to send a result. Actually, the process tool is tied to a session ID; if the session ends, the background process might be terminated? I'm not sure. The process tool says: \"Manage running exec sessions: list, poll, log, write, send-keys, submit, paste, kill.\" It suggests that exec sessions are tied to the current agent session? Actually, when you start an exec with background:true, it creates a managed session that persists even if you stop polling? It says \"Run in background immediately\". So the process continues. And you can later poll it using its sessionId from the same session? But if the session ends, you might lose the sessionId. However, you could list sessions? The `process list` shows sessions for the current session? The tool description: \"Manage running exec sessions (list, poll, log, write, send-keys, submit, paste, kill).\" I think it's per-session processes.\n\nThus, if I start a background exec and then the session ends, I might not be able to retrieve it. But the user is still in the same session? Actually, the conversation continues; I can send a message that I started it and then later, when it's done, I could look at its output and reply. I can do a loop: start background, then repeatedly poll until done, then get output and present. But that would block my turn; I could be doing other things? The session is interactive; I should be responsive.\n\nMaybe I should just start it and then provide instructions for the user to check the output themselves using `process` commands. That's not user-friendly.\n\nGiven these constraints, maybe there's a simpler method: use `openclaw message` to send a command to an agent that will do the search and reply. That agent could be a separate session that runs a skill that does web search. But we don't have such skill pre-installed.\n\nWait, there is a `webhooks` command that might help. The webhooks command can send HTTP requests to a URL. That's not for fetching news.\n\nWhat about using the `oracle` skill but with `--engine api` and using a model that has internet access? Not via API; OpenAI's API models don't have live web access unless using browsing feature which is not part of the standard API. Actually, some models like `gpt-4-turbo` with `browsing` is not available via API? It's only in ChatGPT. So API mode won't browse.\n\nThus, only browser mode does actual browsing.\n\nMaybe I can use a simpler approach: fetch from an RSS feed that is plain and accessible, like Wikipedia's news? For Liu Yifei, maybe there's a Wikipedia RSS? Not standard.\n\nAlternatively, use a service like `https://newsapi.org`? That requires API key.\n\nPerhaps the environment has restrictions on outbound HTTP except to apt repositories? But example.com worked. So some sites work.\n\nCould be that Bing and Google block the request due to missing Accept-Language or other headers. I could try to set more headers. But maybe they detect it's a bot and block.\n\nLet's try a news site that provides straightforward RSS, like CNN or BBC, but they may not have Liu Yifei. But we want Chinese news, so maybe we should fetch from a Chinese news portal that offers RSS. For example, Sina News: http://rss.sina.com.cn/news/allnews/mixed.rss? Not sure. Or NetEase: http://news.163.com/rss/0.xml? But that's general. And they might contain Liu Yifei if it's top news? Not guaranteed.\n\nMaybe I should use a search engine that returns JSON results via an API that doesn't require key: for example, DuckDuckGo Instant Answer API? It's limited.\n\nBetter: Use the Bing Search API? That's paid.\n\nGiven the difficulty, perhaps the best is to use oracle with browser mode. I can set it up as a background process and then later, when it finishes, I can read the stored session. But I need to present the results to the user. However, I could also simply start the oracle and then, if it finishes within a reasonable time (maybe 15-30 mins?), I could wait? But the user might be waiting for immediate reply. Typically, an assistant should not make the user wait for a long time without response. I should respond quickly. I could say: \"I'm starting a search that will take 10-60 minutes. I'll let you know when it's done. You can also check the oracle session.\" That would be acceptable.\n\nBut the user asked \"搜集网上关于刘亦菲的新闻\" - they want me to gather the news. I could try to do it quickly using a different approach: use a Chinese search engine like Sogou? I'm not sure if accessible.\n\nGiven the environment, I might try using `wget` or `curl` with a Baidu news RSS but with proper parameters and maybe using a different endpoint: I recall that Baidu News RSS can be accessed at: `http://news.baidu.com/ns?word=刘亦菲&tn=newsRSS`. I used https earlier, maybe it's http. Let's try http.","thinkingSignature":"reasoning"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_d56b769aadf940928c613ed1","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"curl -s -L \"http://news.baidu.com/ns?word=刘亦菲&tn=newsRSS\" | head -c 1000","timeout":15}}],"api":"openai-completions","provider":"openrouter","model":"stepfun/step-3.5-flash:free","usage":{"input":26438,"output":4049,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":30487,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1773235125561}}
